Fluorescence titration of C-dots with Fe(III) ions gradually decreased their PL intensity at 452 nm reaching an almost complete quenching at 135 μM Fe(III) ions (Fig. 3B and C
                        ). The selective PL quenching of the C-dots by Fe(III) ions exhibited a linear relationship with the concentration of Fe(III), as shown in Fig. 3D. The limit of detection (LOD) for Fe (III) was found to be 0.77 μM (correlation coefficient of 0.997) by using the formula δ/m, where δ denotes the standard deviation and m represents the slope of the linear fit. Remarkably, the LOD we observed in this study is much lower than the limit of Fe(III) ions (5.36 μM) concentrations proposed by the World Health Organization (WHO) [81] suggesting that C-dots could be efficiently used for Fe(III) ion sensing with high selectivity. Moreover, this study demonstrates that the detection limit of curauá-derived C-dots is comparable to, or lower than, those reported in earlier reports for C-dots derived from other biomass resources [Table 1
                        ].

Next, we sought to determine the time course of the uptake of C-dots by B16F1 and J774.A1 cells. To this end, cells were incubated with 100 μg/mL C-dots and analyzed by flow cytometry after 1, 24, 48 and 72 h of incubation at 37 °C. The emission of C-dots was analyzed in 5 different fluorescence channels namely Pacific Blue, FITC, PE, PE-CY7 and APC to cover a wide spectrum of emissions. As shown in Fig. 8
                        , the highest emission of C-dots could be detected in the FITC and PE channels in both cell types, whereas C-dot emission in the Pacific Blue, PE-CY7 and APC was lower (Figs. 8, S5 and S6). It was also clear that increasing the incubation time, resulted in a higher emission signal in all channels (Fig.8), although we did not observe a large difference of C-dots emission at 24, 48 and 72 h (Figs. 8, S5 and S6). These observations were corroborated by the calculation of the mean fluorescence intensity (MFI) from three independent flow cytometry measurements for each channel and time point. Thus, our findings demonstrate the suitability of C-dots for flow cytometry analysis and showed that the highest emission levels were observed in the FITC and PE channels at each time point (Fig. 9
                        ). Furthermore, these data highlight a different time course and magnitude of the internalization of C-dots in B16F1 and J774.A1 cells (Fig. 9).
